               <p>501. <persName id="def1-501-18600507" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-501-18600507" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-501-18600507" type="age" value="19"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-501-18600507" type="surname" value="BARRETT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-501-18600507" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES BARRETT</hi> (19)</persName>, and <persName id="def2-501-18600507" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-501-18600507" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-501-18600507" type="age" value="19"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-501-18600507" type="surname" value="STREAKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-501-18600507" type="given" value="REUBEN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">REUBEN STREAKER</hi> (19)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18600507-501-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18600507-501-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18600507-501-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="forgery"></interp>, Feloniously forging and uttering an order for the payment of 153<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., with intent to defraud.</rs>
               </p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070228"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BRAND</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-761" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-761" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-761" type="surname" value="TURNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-761" type="given" value="JOHN PEACOCK"></interp>JOHN PEACOCK TURNER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am cashier of the Unity Bank in Cannon-street—on 16th April this cheque for 153<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., which I have in my hand, was pre<lb></lb>sented to me—the name of Talleman is at the foot of it—Mr. Talleman was a customer of ours—I cashed the cheque, believing this to be his signature, but I have since discovered it to be a forgery—it is very much like his signa<lb></lb>ture—I cannot swear to the person who presented the cheque—Streaker is like the man—in cashing it, I gave a 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note, 5 ten-pouud notes, and 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in money—these are some of the notes that I gave.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> They are the same numbers you mean as those that were paid? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I only swear to them by that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-762" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-762" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-762" type="surname" value="TALLEMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-762" type="given" value="HARRIS"></interp>HARRIS TALLEMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a general warehouseman, living in Houndsditch—I keep au account at the Unity Bank—this order for a cheque book is not in my writing—I never signed this cheque, but it is very much like my signatnre—I know the prisoner Barrett; he was in my employment for about five or six weeks, about five or six months ago—he had frequent opportunities of seeing my writing—he has transacted business for me at the Unity Bank; taken cheques there, and received money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-763" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-763" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-763" type="surname" value="PAYNE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-763" type="given" value="RALPH"></interp>RALPH PAYNE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of Mr. Goad, jeweller, in the Borough—on 16th April I saw Barrett about 8 o'clock in the evening—he looked at two rings which would come to about 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and asked me if I could give him change for a 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note—I told him I would see if he would put his name at the back—he put a name at the back of the note—I said I was afraid I should not be able to give him change for it—he said he was going as far as the Elephant and Castle, and would call again—this is the note—I read the name—it was "J. Williams, 18, City-road"—I know this note by the name—he went out of the shop, leaving the note—I kept it till he returned, and then told him that I was afraid I should not be able to change it for him—I asked him where he got it from—he said that he had a friend who came into 3,000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I told him I was afraid I should not be able to change it for him, and he said he would go and ask his friend if he could lend him the money—he returned, and said that he was not able to find him—I told him if he left the note I should be able to change it for him in the morning—he said that he should be going past the Bank of England himself in the morning, and could get it cashed—he left me 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. as deposit on the rings, and weut away, taking the note with him—Mr. Lyons afterwards came and brought the note—he took it away again with him—I went and gave information to the police—I went to Mr. Lyons' shop that evening and saw Barrett there—there was a policeman there, who asked him if he had any more notes, and he denied having any more—I said that I had seen him with some more notes in a bag when he took the 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note out—I saw a woman in Mr. Lyons' shop with him—he had not given me a 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note that evening to change, nor had I given him a 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note that evening.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-764" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-764" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-764" type="surname" value="LYONS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-764" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES LYONS</persName>
                  </hi>. I and my father keep a clothing establishment in the Borough—on the evening of 16th of April, Barrett came into our shop about a quarter to 9, accompanied by a young woman—he selected a stock of clothes, value 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. and offered me this 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note—he told me that he had just bought two rings of Mr. Goad, had paid him with a 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note and had received this note in part change, and wished me to change it—I did not like his appearance—I told him that if that was the case, I would go over to Mr. Goad, and perhaps he would givemegold for it—I went to Mr. Goad's and saw Mr. Payne—I afterwards returned to my shop, and detained Barrett in the shop while Mr. Payne went for the police—he was eventually taken</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070229"></xptr>
               <p>into custody, and the girl also—Mr. Payne said in his presence that he saw him with other notes; but I saw nothing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-765" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-765" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-765" type="surname" value="PACKMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-765" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT PACKMAN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City-Policeman</hi>). On the 17th, from some information I received, I went to Stone's-end police-station, and saw Barrett there—I told him I was sorry to see him there, and asked him if his friends were aware that he was there—he said he believed they were, but he had not seen them—I said I understood he was there about Borne notes—he said, "Yes—I am; I should like to tell you the truth about it"—I have known him some years—he knows me to be an officer—I then said, "You know I am a police officer, and whatever you say I shall have to make use of in evidence against you before the Magistrate"—he then said, "I received <hi rend="italic">them</hi> notes from a person last night in front of the Mansion-house"—he told me that his grandmother had lately left him between 2000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and 3000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and that this was some of the money to go on with—he meaut the grandmother of the person from whom he had received them; he said, "He gave me these notes to get cashed for him"—I said, "Is that man a stranger to you?"—he said, "No; his name is Reuben William Streaker, and he lives some<lb></lb>where near Kenuington-park"—I had, previous to seeing the prisoner, seen the four notes which the officer had—I said, "I see on the back of some of the notes there is the name of Sole and Turner, and they are solicitors in Aldermanbury, close to where you live"—he said, "Yes, I wrote the name of Sole and Turner on one of the notes, but not on all of them"—I said, "I saw you with a man in Finsbury-circus two or three days ago, who was a stranger to me"—he said, "That is the man I had the notes of"—I had seen him with another man as I told him—I saw the two prisoners together about three days previous to Barrett's being taken in custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Barrett.</hi> I wrote the name of Williams on the note. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I did not have hem in my hand—I only saw them in another person's hand; I should not know them—I saw the name of Sole and Turner on one of them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-766" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-766" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-766" type="surname" value="TIGHE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-766" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY TIGHE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, M</hi> 226). On 16th April, I took Barrett at the shop of Mr. Lyons, clothier, High-street, Borough—there was a female in his company—this 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note was passed to me in Barrett's presence by Mr. Lyons—I asked Barrett where he got it from—he said he had been paid his wages in a 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note, which he had chauged for two 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. notes—he said his employers were wine merchants—I asked him where the other 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note was—he said that he had given one 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note to a friend at the Elephant and Castle—I asked him if he had the bag containing the notes—he said he had not—I asked the female, in his presence—she said she had not the bag—not being satisfied with them I took them to the station—the male prisoner gave his address Barber's hall, Monkwell-street—Whiffin, the female, gave her's 54. Wood-street, Cheapside—she was searched by the female searcher, Mrs. Fenson, from whom I received this bag with the contents—it contained a 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note, and two 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. notes—those are the notes which Mr. Turner has just seen—on the 17th, I called at 54, Wood-street, the address given by the female, and there I saw Streaker leaving the house—I then recollected having to seen him the previous night standing oustide Mr. Lyons'Shop during the time I was speaking to Barrett—I did not say anything to him on this occasion—I afterwards apprehended him—I told him that I wanted him for being coucerned with a man named Barrett, and a female named Whiffin, for stealing a quantity of notes—he said, "The notes are not stolen; I have done wrong, but I was led into it by Barrett"—I took him to the station, searched him, and found on him this piece of paper, which I now produce—the sums stated on this piece of paper amount to 153<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070230"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">J. P. TURNER</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you any means of knowing what time of the day the note was presented? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I know from my books that it was between 11 and 3 o'clock—I go out at 3 o'clock, and it was before I went out—I have the book with the list of the notes which I paid away—it is about the middle of the day's entries in the book—from that I suppose that it was about the middle of the day's business; probably about 1 or 2 o'clock—I was asked for a 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note and five tens.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-767" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-767" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-767" type="surname" value="FENSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-767" type="given" value="SARAH ANN"></interp>SARAH ANN FENSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am female searcher at Stone's-end police-station, Borough—I searched a woman named Whiffin, and found on her a 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note in a bag, and two 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. notes crumpled up—I delivered them to Tighe.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Streaker's defence.</hi> The cheque was written by Barrett, and I presented it.</p>
               <p>
